**Definition:** A class should have one, and only one, reason to change. 'Reason to change' = the stakeholder whose requirement changes would force a modification.

```java
// ❌ BAD: OrderService has three reasons to change
class OrderService {
    void placeOrder(Order o) {
        validate(o);           // validation rules change
        db.save(o);            // DB schema changes
        emailService.send(o);  // email template changes
    }
}

// ✅ GOOD: each class has one reason to change
class OrderValidator  { void validate(Order o) { ... } }
class OrderRepository { void save(Order o)     { ... } }
class OrderNotifier   { void notify(Order o)   { ... } }
class OrderService {
    void placeOrder(Order o) {
        validator.validate(o);
        repository.save(o);
        notifier.notify(o);
    }
}
```

**Practical signal:** if you describe a class with 'and' (validates AND persists AND emails), it violates SRP. In Spring, this maps neatly to Controller → Service → Repository layers — each layer has one concern.

**Inheritance:** compile-time relationship; tight coupling to the base class. Changes to the base class affect all subclasses (fragile base class problem).

**Composition:** wire behaviour together via interfaces. Swap implementations at runtime or test time.

```java
// ❌ Inheritance — Logger is tightly coupled to FileOutput
class FileOutput { void write(String s) { /* file I/O */ } }
class Logger extends FileOutput { void log(String msg) { write("[LOG] " + msg); } }
// Problem: can't swap to DB output without changing class hierarchy

// ✅ Composition — Logger depends on interface, not implementation
interface OutputChannel { void write(String s); }
class FileChannel    implements OutputChannel { ... }
class DatabaseChannel implements OutputChannel { ... }

class Logger {
    private final OutputChannel channel;
    Logger(OutputChannel channel) { this.channel = channel; } // inject at runtime
    void log(String msg) { channel.write("[LOG] " + msg); }
}
```

**Use inheritance when:** the 'is-a' relationship is stable and the base class is designed for extension (Liskov-safe). Use composition by default — it's the more flexible, testable choice (Gang of Four: 'Favour object composition over class inheritance').

**F — Fast:** runs in < 100ms. No real I/O, no sleep(), no network calls. Use mocks/stubs for external deps.

**I — Independent:** tests don't depend on each other. Any test can run first, last, or alone. No shared mutable state between tests (reset @BeforeEach).

**R — Repeatable:** same result every time, in any environment (CI, Mac, Windows). No randomness, no time-sensitive logic. Stub Date/time with a fixed Clock.

**S — Self-validating:** either passes or fails — no manual log inspection. Use assertThat/assertEquals, not print statements.

**T — Timely:** written at the same time as the code (TDD) or immediately after. Tests written months later are harder to write and less likely to be written.

```java
// ✅ Good unit test
@Test
void order_with_negative_amount_should_throw() {
    OrderService service = new OrderService(mockRepo, mockNotifier);
    assertThatThrownBy(() -> service.placeOrder(new Order(-1)))
        .isInstanceOf(IllegalArgumentException.class)
        .hasMessageContaining("amount");
}
```

```java
// ❌ VIOLATES OCP — adding a new discount type requires editing this class
class DiscountCalculator {
    double calculate(Order o, String type) {
        if (type.equals("STUDENT")) return o.total * 0.1;
        if (type.equals("SENIOR"))  return o.total * 0.15;
        // must edit this file to add new discount
        return 0;
    }
}

// ✅ FOLLOWS OCP — new discount = new class, no edits
interface DiscountStrategy { double apply(Order o); }

class StudentDiscount implements DiscountStrategy {
    public double apply(Order o) { return o.total * 0.1; }
}
class SeniorDiscount implements DiscountStrategy {
    public double apply(Order o) { return o.total * 0.15; }
}

class DiscountCalculator {
    double calculate(Order o, DiscountStrategy strategy) {
        return strategy.apply(o);
    }
}

// With Java 8+ lambdas — DiscountStrategy is a functional interface:
calculator.calculate(order, o -> o.total * 0.2); // 20% off, zero new classes
```

**Key insight:** OCP doesn't mean zero changes ever — it means the stable core logic is closed, while extension points (interfaces/lambdas) are open.

**Test doubles taxonomy (Gerard Meszaros):**
- **Dummy:** placeholder — passed but never used (null, empty object)
- **Stub:** returns pre-programmed responses (`when(repo.findById(1)).thenReturn(user)`)
- **Spy:** partial stub — wraps a real object, some methods stubbed, others real
- **Mock:** pre-programmed with expectations about which calls they should receive; fails if unexpected calls occur
- **Fake:** real working implementation (e.g. H2 in-memory DB instead of PostgreSQL)

```java
// Stub — just return a value
when(paymentGateway.charge(any())).thenReturn(PaymentResult.success());

// Mock — also verify the call happened
orderService.placeOrder(order);
verify(paymentGateway, times(1)).charge(argThat(p -> p.amount() == order.total()));
verify(emailService, never()).sendFailure(any()); // failure path NOT called
```

**Rule of thumb:** stub queries (return data), mock commands (verify side effects happened). Over-mocking (verifying every call) makes tests brittle — they break when implementation changes even if behaviour is correct.

**Barbara Liskov's definition (1987):** If S is a subtype of T, objects of type T may be replaced with objects of type S without altering the correctness of the program.

**The Rectangle/Square problem:**
```java
class Rectangle {
    int width, height;
    void setWidth(int w)  { this.width = w; }
    void setHeight(int h) { this.height = h; }
    int area() { return width * height; }
}

class Square extends Rectangle {
    @Override void setWidth(int w)  { this.width = this.height = w; } // maintains square invariant
    @Override void setHeight(int h) { this.width = this.height = h; }
}

// LSP violation — this code breaks for Square
void printArea(Rectangle r) {
    r.setWidth(5);
    r.setHeight(4);
    // Expected: 5 × 4 = 20
    System.out.println(r.area()); // Rectangle: 20 ✓ Square: 16 ✗
}
```

**Fix:** Don't extend — use a common Shape interface with immutable dimensions, or make Rectangle immutable. The invariant 'setWidth doesn't change height' is a precondition that Square breaks.

**Practical LSP checks:** subclasses should not throw exceptions not declared by the base class, should not tighten preconditions, and should not weaken postconditions.

**Problem (telescoping constructor):**
```java
// Which argument is which? Easy to swap two strings.
new Email("alice@x.com", "bob@x.com", "Hello", null, true, false);
```

**Builder solution:**
```java
Email email = Email.builder()
    .from("alice@x.com")
    .to("bob@x.com")
    .subject("Hello")
    .htmlBody(true)
    .build();
```

**In Java:** use Lombok's `@Builder` annotation to generate the builder automatically:
```java
@Builder
@Value // immutable + all-args constructor
public class Email {
    String from, to, subject, body;
    boolean htmlBody;
}
```

**When NOT to use Builder:** for simple objects with 1–3 required params, a constructor or static factory method is simpler and less boilerplate. Builder adds value at 4+ params or when some are optional.

**1. Long Method → Extract Method**
A method does too many things. Extract cohesive chunks into named private methods.
```java
// ❌ 60-line placeOrder() method
// ✅ validateOrder(); chargePayment(); updateInventory(); sendConfirmation();
```

**2. Feature Envy → Move Method**
A method uses data from another class more than its own.
```java
// ❌ OrderService.calculateShipping(Address address) uses Address fields heavily
// ✅ Move calculateShipping() to Address class — the data and behaviour live together
```

**3. Primitive Obsession → Introduce Value Object**
Using primitives (String, int) where a rich object would add safety and meaning.
```java
// ❌ createUser(String email, String phone, int age)
// ✅
record Email(String value) { Email { validate(value); } }
record Phone(String value) { Phone { validate(value); } }
createUser(Email email, Phone phone, Age age); // compiler catches swapped args
```

**4. Bonus — Duplicate Code → Extract Method/Template Method**
Same logic copy-pasted. Extract into a shared method. If in sibling classes, use Template Method or move to a shared utility.
